WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.000
Continue in our discussion of testing. Let's now talk about operational testing.

00:19.000 --> 00:39.000
Continue in our discussion of testing. Let's now talk about operational testing.

00:39.000 --> 00:43.000
There's three major types of operational testing that we're going to talk about.

00:43.000 --> 00:47.000
Rum, synthetic transactions and progression testing. Let's start with rum.

00:47.000 --> 00:57.000
Rum stands for real user monitoring. Real user monitoring is simply the concept that you watch your log files to see what real users are doing with your system.

00:57.000 --> 01:04.000
Are they when they're accessing your website? Are there certain error messages popping up like 404 or a file mod found or something like that?

01:04.000 --> 01:11.000
So, watching your log files to see how real users are watching your system is known as real user monitoring.

01:11.000 --> 01:20.000
Now, what about synthetic transactions? Synthetic transactions is this idea that we synthesize or we create transactions on a system.

01:20.000 --> 01:25.000
How do we do that? Well, think of it as creating little software scripts or bots.

01:25.000 --> 01:29.000
And these little software scripts or bots will perform certain functions.

01:29.000 --> 01:32.000
So, maybe a good way to think about this is an online banking system.

01:32.000 --> 01:39.000
An online banking system has all sorts of functionality. You can log in. You can check your account balance. You can transfer funds.

01:39.000 --> 01:46.000
You could write synthetic transactions that would test or would perform each of these operations. One of them would log in.

01:46.000 --> 01:50.000
Another would transfer funds. Another would check an account balance.

01:50.000 --> 01:56.000
And if you write a synthetic transaction or a little bot that tests each of these pieces of functionality,

01:56.000 --> 02:05.000
then you can run all those transactions, those synthetic transactions, and see all the functions, for instance, on your website working correctly.

02:05.000 --> 02:12.000
And there's another really cool usage for synthetic transactions. And that is, what if instead of running these one at a time?

02:12.000 --> 02:21.000
What if you were to run 10,000 of them simultaneously? What would that test? Well, that would test load or performance of your application.

02:21.000 --> 02:26.000
See how your application performs if it's getting hit by a whole lack of users like on Black Friday.

02:26.000 --> 02:31.000
So, you can use synthetic transactions to test the performance of your application.

02:31.000 --> 02:39.000
Here's a really good test question that sometimes comes up. What would be the most accurate environment in which you perform synthetic transactions?

02:39.000 --> 02:47.000
And the answer is production. If you truly want to know how your system is going to react to a huge load,

02:47.000 --> 02:53.000
the best environment to test in is production. Are you going to be extremely careful about doing that? Of course.

02:53.000 --> 03:01.000
You're all sorts of testing and dev and so forth, so forth first. But if you truly want to know how your application is going to react, test and production.

03:02.000 --> 03:06.000
The next type of testing we're going to talk about is regression testing.

03:06.000 --> 03:15.000
And regression testing is simply the idea that if you make a change to a system, not only do you want to check to make sure all the new functionalities working correctly,

03:15.000 --> 03:20.000
but also make sure that all the existing functionality keeps working properly.

03:20.000 --> 03:29.000
That is regression testing. It's this concept of testing code or testing systems to make sure you didn't break anything when you implement a change.

03:29.000 --> 03:35.000
With any of the testing that we've talked about in the last few modules, it's important to have very clear test results.

03:35.000 --> 03:41.000
To know, for instance, did your test actually pass or did it fail? You don't want the result of the test to be, eh, maybe.

03:41.000 --> 03:49.000
You wanted to be, yes, it passed or no, it didn't pass. And you want to be able to have the right level of detail in the test results,

03:49.000 --> 03:58.000
the right metrics reported to the right people. The way that you report the results of a test is going to vary depending on who the audience of that test result is and what it is they're looking to see.

03:58.000 --> 04:00.000
We're looking to see.

